Next, we split the data in train and test

data_train <- ts(data[1:80], start=c(1961,1) ,frequency=4)
data_train %>% ggtsdisplay()

data_test <- ts(data[81:84], start=c(1981,1) ,frequency=4)
data_test %>% ggtsdisplay(lag.max = 40)

It is a non stationary Time Series. Non constant mean, non constant variance. Trend, Seasonality both present.

###Step 2: Box-Cox transformation to stabilize the variance

lamda <- BoxCox.lambda(data_train)
lamda
## [1] 0.1803894

Examine the sample ACF and sample PACF of log(x) and sqrt(x)

par(mfrow=c(3,3))
plot(data_train)
acf(data_train)
pacf(data_train)
plot(data_train^0.5)
acf(data_train^0.5)
pacf(data_train^0.5)
plot(log(data_train))
acf(log(data_train))
pacf(log(data_train))

The best plot for non constant variance is obtained by taking log of time series. Hence, we continue with log transformation.

Taking log of original data

data_train %>% log() %>% ggtsdisplay(lag.max=40)

data_train %>% log() %>% adf.test()
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  .
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.3273, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.8509
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

H0: Non stationary H1: Stationary As p-value > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Non stationary time series.

ACF= Slowly decreases. PACF= High spike at lag 1.

Hence, we take first order seasonal difference

###Step 3: Taking first order difference to remove non constant mean

data_train %>% log() %>% diff(lag=4) %>% ggtsdisplay(lag.max=40)

data_train %>% log() %>% diff(lag=4) %>% adf.test()
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  .
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.0763, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.1362
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

H0: Non stationary H1: Stationary As p-value > 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Non stationary time series.

We take first order difference of the time series.

data_train %>% log() %>% diff(lag=4) %>% diff() %>%  ggtsdisplay(lag.max=40)

data_train %>% log() %>% diff(lag=4) %>% diff() %>%  adf.test()
## Warning in adf.test(.): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  .
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.6486, Lag order = 4, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

H0: Non stationary H1: Stationary As p-value < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis. Stationary time series.

ACF= Slowly decreases. PACF= High spike at lag 1.

Next, we try to run auto arima function to get a baseline model

###Step 4: Fitting a Model

  1. ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4] using auto.arima
fit0 <- data_train %>% auto.arima()
fit0
## Series: . 
## ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4]

## Coefficients:
##           ma1    sar1

## sigma^2 estimated as 0.1967:  log likelihood=-44.91

checkresiduals(fit0)

## 
##  Ljung-Box test
## 
## data:  Residuals from ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4]
## Q* = 13.45, df = 6, p-value = 0.03642
## 
## Model df: 2.   Total lags used: 8

As in the original plot of data_train obtained after taking log, first order difference and seasonal difference, for non seasonal, we see 2 spikes at 0 and 4 in PACF and one spike at lag 0 in ACF followed by exponential decay.This looks like MA(1) model

For seasonal component, we observe high spike at lag 4 in PACF and non significant spikes in ACF. This looks like AR(1) model.

  1. ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4]

The residuals for the fit1 behave like white noise. Both the coeffiecients are also significant. But, we can check for other models also.

For non seasonal component, we can observe 2 spikes at 0 and 4 in PACF and can try AR(2) model. For seaonal component, we can go ahead with MA(1)

We can try ARMA(1,1) for non seasonal component.

As the BIC value of ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4] is the least as compared to other models. We can use this model for forecasting.

#final model
fit4<-(data_train %>% Arima(order=c(0,1,1), seasonal=c(1,1,0), lambda= 0.18, include.constant = FALSE))
fit4
## Series: . 
## ARIMA(0,1,1)(1,1,0)[4] 
## Box Cox transformation: lambda= 0.18 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1     sar1
##       -0.6955  -0.2832
## s.e.   0.0962   0.1158
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.01198:  log likelihood=59.94
## AIC=-113.87   AICc=-113.53   BIC=-106.92
coeftest(fit4)
## 
## z test of coefficients:
## 
##       Estimate Std. Error z value  Pr(>|z|)    
## ma1  -0.695477   0.096155 -7.2329 4.728e-13 ***
## sar1 -0.283250   0.115810 -2.4458   0.01445 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Both ma1 and sar1 are significant as the p value is less than 0.05.

We can use lyung-Box test to check for autocorrelation in the lag

Box.test(resid(fit4), lag=10, type= "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resid(fit4)
## X-squared = 7.7826, df = 10, p-value = 0.6501

H0: No autocorrelation in the lags-> Data is like white noise H1: Autocorrelation in the lags

p-value> 0.05, no autocorrelation in the lags. We fail to reject the null hypothesis.

###Step 5: Overfitting

Using (p,q+1) and (p+1,q) we make 2 models and check for overfitting

fit5<-(data_train %>% Arima(order=c(1,1,1),seasonal=c(1,1,1),lambda= 0.18, include.constant = FALSE))
coeftest(fit5)

In the first model, ma1 is the one coefficient which is significant. In second model, ma1 and sar1 are the only one significant.

Accuracy-> 100 - 2.17 = 97.82

###Step 8: Equation of Model

The model can be described by the following equation:

X_{t} = 0.695477a_{t-1} + -0.2832X{t-4}
